'''Ernest R. Ball''' (  -  ) was a   and , most famous for composing the music for the song "" in 1912.
Born in , Ball received formal music training at the .  His nascent career was much buoyed by , then a state senator of , who asked Ball to write music for some lyrics he wrote. Ball did, and the song "Will You Love Me In December as You Do In May?" became a hit.  Walker later became known as "Dapper Jimmy Walker", Mayor of , a fortunate event for Ball's career.
Ball accompanied singers, sang in  and wrote sentimental ballads, mostly with Irish themes.<ref>Laurie, Joe, Jr. ''Vaudeville: From the Honky-tonks to the Palace.'' New York: Henry Holt, 1953. p. 328.</ref>  He collaborated with Chauncey Olcott on many songs including "When Irish Eyes are Smiling," for which Olcott composed lyrics. He became a charter member of  in 1907, and wrote many American standards. He died in his dressing room at the Yost Theatre in  while on tour with "Ernie Ball and His Gang" an act starring Ball and a male octet.<ref>Slide, Anthony. ''The Encyclopedia of Vaudeville.'' Westport, Connecticut, Greenwood Press, 1994. p. 22.</ref> Ball was posthumously inducted into the  in 1970.
